:::summary
Geoffrey Chaucer (c. 1343–1400) was the greatest English poet of the Middle Ages and the "Father of English Literature" — the first major writer to use the English vernacular as a vehicle for serious literary art. His masterpiece, *The Canterbury Tales*, presents a group of pilgrims traveling to the shrine of Thomas Becket at Canterbury, each telling stories along the way, and in doing so creates a panoramic portrait of medieval English society in all its variety, humor, pathos, and moral complexity. No writer before Shakespeare surpassed Chaucer's ability to create living human characters — comic, tender, corrupt, devout — and to tell their stories with irony, compassion, and sheer delight.
:::

